Author: Chanda Prescod-Weinstein

Title: A Libertarian Walks Into a Bear: The Utopian Plot to Liberate an American Town (And Some Bears)
Author: Matthew Hongoltz-Hetling
My Review: An entertaining look at a social experiment in Nrw Hampshire. I learned a lot about the libertarian principles (and their flaws when drawn to the extreme). I do wish the author did less to "other" the group, but it was fair enough to still be a great read. .

Author: Sebastian Mallaby

Title: User Friendly: How the Hidden Rules of Design Are Changing the Way We Live, Work, and Play
Author: Cliff Kuang
My Review: I'm torn on this. In many ways, it feels like the worthy sequel to "Design of Everyday Things." However, outside of the first few chapters which were quite good, I found most of the insights and stories forgettable. A non-design-practitioner may find it more interesting!

Title: Regulatory Hacking: A Playbook for Startups
Author: Evan Burfield
My Review: Burfield covers how startups can navigate regulations in complex industires, or even use them as an advantage. Overall, I thought this was a solid overview. The best chapter with new learnings for me was about government procurement. My critique is that most of the content was just a slight tweak on normal startup tactics, so this would be an even better read for someone just entering entrepreneurship.

Title: Taste Makers: Seven Immigrant Women Who Revolutionized Food in America
Author: Mayukh Sen

Title: The Storyteller: Tales of Life and Music
Author: Dave Grohl
My Review: Fun, easy, Dave Grohl. These stories were simultaneously more prolific and more down to earth than I expected.

Title: The Omnivore's Dilemma: A Natural History of Four Meals
Author: Michael Pollan
My Review: Fantastic primer on meat and produce, carnivores and vegetarians, and ranchers and farmers. I found Pollan's neutrality, openness, and storytelling excellent, hooking me to both sides of the debate around the future of food and ag.

Title: Rules of Civility
Author: Amor Towles

Title: Den of Thieves
Author: James B. Stewart

Title: The Man Who Solved the Market: How Jim Simons Launched the Quant Revolution
Author: Gregory Zuckerman
My Review: Loved the ups and downs of this entrepreneurial story. I do wish the author went into more technical depth on how the algorithms worked instead of chalking them up as vague "better data" or "genius ideas."

Title: Cod: A Biography of the Fish that Changed the World
Author: Mark Kurlansky
My Review: I liked this short microhistory for the most part, but I must admit my interest waned around 2/3 through. Maybe too micro.

Title: A Shot to Save the World: The Remarkable Race and Ground-Breaking Science Behind the Covid-19 Vaccines
Author: Gregory Zuckerman
My Review: This was the perfect time to read the story of the Covid vaccine and the science and history behind vaccines in general, MRNA, and biotech startups. I loved it! The writing was narrative enough to flow but nonfiction packed enough to help me learn new information. I hope there's a sequel about post-Delta developments.

Title: Liquid Rules: The Delightful and Dangerous Substances That Flow Through Our Lives
Author: Mark Miodownik
My Review: This book uses a meandering anecdote about a plane flight to weave together factoids about different liquids. I learned a few things here and there, but the story felt forced and there were a bit too many fadcescuous but demeaning comments about random inconsequential characters. I loved the author's other book, "Stuff Matters," but didn't like this as much.

Author: Jennifer Egan
My Review: The character vignettes in this story were remarkable – poignant and real feeling. However, the vast web of characters didn't fit together in a way that allowed me to follow the high-level plot.

Title: Atomic Habits: An Easy & Proven Way to Build Good Habits & Break Bad Ones
Author: James Clear
Additional Authors: Gunnar Nyquist, Nagalakshmi Shanmugam, Ondřej Halámek, Aleš Drobek
My Review: I liked this book a lot, which surprised me (having not enjoyed other pop-self-help books like "Grit," "Originals," etc). I can't pinpoint exactly what made it work, but something about the relatable stories, small and actionable nuggets of advice, and chapter summaries made it work. There was a lot of overlap with "The Power of Habit" and "Hooked," but with a strong bent on personal habits, not business or product. I'm actually excited to implement a few tips soon!

Title: The Radium Girls: The Dark Story of America's Shining Women
Author: Kate  Moore
My Review: The content of this book was totally shocking and gruesome. I learned a lot about radium, 1930s working conditions, and the legal system. My main critique here is that it felt like an endless expose with repetitive reporting of similar scenarios. I (and some of my book club) would have preferred to focus on a few of the women with supporting characters, versus an equal coverage of over 30 different people.

Title: The Rise of the Meritocracy
Author: Michael Young

Author: Bethany McLean

Title: Black Cake
Author: Charmaine Wilkerson

Title: Crying in H Mart
Author: Michelle Zauner
My Review: I really liked this memoir for a few reasons. Firstly, it was an insightful and emotional view into the Korean-American experience, where her occasional mindset as an outsider helped me relate to a culture that wasn't my own. Secondly, I didn't realize Zauner was Japanese Breakfast until the very end when she called it out. I think my view would have been tainted if I read it starstruck; instead, her vulnerable stories humanized her and were engaging to read. And the writing was fantastic!

Title: Bicycling with Butterflies: My 10,201-Mile Journey Following the Monarch Migration
Author: Sara Dykman

Title: Thinking, Fast and Slow
Author: Daniel Kahneman

Title: Arriving Today: From Factory to Front Door-Why Everything Has Changed About How and What We Buy
Author: Christopher Mims
My Review: This book connected the dots for a lot of today's modern logistics mysteries. I learned fundamental differences between Amazon, UPS, FedEx, and USPS - right now and directionally into the future. My only criticisms are the author's tendency to be a nonchalant sympathizer for Amazon's most unethical practices, and my lack of an emotional connection to the USB charger through line. Instead of following such a generic product in its journey from manufacture to delivery across the world, I would have preferred to trace something with more stakes or urgency.

Title: Then We Came to the End
Author: Joshua Ferris
My Review: I didn't feel connected to any of the characters or the plot. The workplace scenarios were either boring or hyperbolic, which was disappointing because I was excited to read fiction about designers and the like.

Title: What If? Serious Scientific Answers to Absurd Hypothetical Questions (What If?, #1)
Author: Randall Munroe
My Review: This was a super fun read, with each chapter telling a new wild story. It was surprisingly seamless as an audiobook, even though Munroe is very much a comics artist.

Title: The Artist's Way: A Spiritual Path to Higher Creativity
Author: Julia Cameron
My Review: As much as I wanted to embrace these teachings, the constant spiritual and religious references took me out of the experience. I think it would be more enjoyable for other folks who are more spiritual.

Title: The Anthropocene Reviewed
Author: John Green
My Review: I did enjoy this book, but came in expecting something different. There were several one-liners in here that stuck with me, but I didn't feel super connected to what was more of a memoir than nonfiction.
